than you were perhaps bargaining for.

36
00:01:37,625 --> 00:01:40,267
So let's start out by kind of giving you your bearings a bit

37
00:01:40,327 --> 00:01:42,069
in terms of how that journey stacks up.

38
00:01:43,130 --> 00:01:46,132
So I think what was in people's minds

39
00:01:46,152 --> 00:01:48,774
when they were asking me to do this talk

40
00:01:48,794 --> 00:01:50,275
was the time that I spent at Hide and Seek.

41
00:01:50,555 --> 00:01:55,419
Hide and Seek was a experimental game studio

42
00:01:55,459 --> 00:01:56,259
founded in London.

43
00:01:56,800 --> 00:01:58,481
We branched out and had a New York studio

44
00:01:58,641 --> 00:01:59,662
that I moved over and ran.

45
00:02:00,543 --> 00:02:03,486
And we were kind of best known for very hybrid games.

46
00:02:03,626 --> 00:02:05,648
So often that meant digital worlds with a,

47
00:02:05,868 --> 00:02:07,450
digital games with a real world component

48
00:02:07,610 --> 00:02:10,513
or collaborations between digital game makers

49
00:02:10,814 --> 00:02:12,495
and artists or choreographers,

50
00:02:12,516 --> 00:02:14,638
kind of all points in between.

51
00:02:14,678 --> 00:02:17,841
So here's a super quick survey of some of our projects

52
00:02:17,861 --> 00:02:18,562
that people may have heard of.

53
00:02:19,703 --> 00:02:27,670
Board game remix kit was an early independent project that we did that we designed in the

54
00:02:27,850 --> 00:02:32,434
middle of having a depressing conversation about how much we were all dreading going

55
00:02:32,494 --> 00:02:36,357
home for Christmas, because when you go home at Christmas, somebody pulls out that mostly

56
00:02:36,458 --> 00:02:40,801
broken awful board game from the top of a cabinet and you all have to play Monopoly

57
00:02:40,881 --> 00:02:45,145
or Trivial Pursuits with the cards that are 25 years out of date, so nobody knows any

58
00:02:45,165 --> 00:02:45,786
of the answers anymore.

59
00:02:46,406 --> 00:02:54,950
So Board Game Remix Kit was a physical card set and smartphone app that kind of mashed

60
00:02:55,030 --> 00:02:59,913
up and remixed a bunch of games that you are likely to have, Monopoly, Clue, Druid Pursuit,

61
00:03:00,213 --> 00:03:05,696
Scrabble, and gave you new rule sets or new kind of combined ways of playing them.

62
00:03:05,736 --> 00:03:06,896
Some super, super nice stuff in there.

63
00:03:06,936 --> 00:03:07,297
That was fun.

64
00:03:08,797 --> 00:03:13,544
We made an iPhone game called The Show Must Go On, which is the world's first opera platformer.

65
00:03:13,564 --> 00:03:16,328
This was in collaboration with the Royal Opera House.

66
00:03:16,469 --> 00:03:21,215
Cast you as a put-upon stage manager who was trying to get the show...

67
00:03:23,695 --> 00:03:28,117
up and running, but it was in the course of finding out that everything had gone wrong.

68
00:03:28,618 --> 00:03:31,739
The costumes had got messed up, the set hadn't been built, the sheet music for the orchestra

69
00:03:31,759 --> 00:03:37,563
had blown away, and you'd play a bunch of kind of one step above WarioWare little puzzle

70
00:03:37,583 --> 00:03:39,004
games to solve those problems.

71
00:03:39,964 --> 00:03:45,989
And then at the end of it you would watch the performance that happened as a result of your preparations.

72
00:03:46,350 --> 00:03:49,472
If you played well, then you got a little nice animation where everything went great.

73
00:03:49,893 --> 00:03:56,178
If you messed up, then you got a little dynamically generated animation where things went wrong depending on which games you had failed in.

74
00:03:56,398 --> 00:04:03,484
So if you found all the sheet music, then you got a gorgeous orchestral recording of the real Royal Opera House Orchestra playing the score.

75
00:04:04,025 --> 00:04:05,346
If you didn't, you got a terrible...

76
00:04:06,422 --> 00:04:08,164
janky chiptune version that we made.

77
00:04:08,885 --> 00:04:11,567
The stunts go wrong, the costumes change around.

78
00:04:11,908 --> 00:04:12,869
Cute, fun, nice thing.

79
00:04:14,130 --> 00:04:16,993
This is Newer Games, which was a city-wide game

80
00:04:17,033 --> 00:04:20,096
that we ran on New Year's Eve in Edinburgh a few years ago.

81
00:04:20,116 --> 00:04:22,658
New Year's Eve is a massive celebration in Edinburgh

82
00:04:24,220 --> 00:04:28,203
and they wanted to follow it up with another huge public.

83
00:04:29,204 --> 00:04:33,407
event the next day and so we ran a series of distributed games across the whole city

84
00:04:34,068 --> 00:04:36,970
where you could play and collect tokens. We put you in a team and you were

85
00:04:39,171 --> 00:04:43,734
trying to win the... whichever team won, that team earned the right to set the...

86
00:04:44,314 --> 00:04:47,296
give a blessing to the city for the rest of the year, give a tone for the city for the rest of the year.

87
00:04:47,356 --> 00:04:47,597
So the

88
00:04:48,337 --> 00:04:52,700
National Poet of Scotland wrote two blessings, one for each of the two teams and then depending on which one won that was going

89
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:57,303
to set the tone for the rest of the year. So you collect tokens and did things and danced in the streets and wore ribbons.

90
00:04:58,344 --> 00:05:01,909
And then the hub of the game was this huge central square underneath Edinburgh Castle

91
00:05:02,369 --> 00:05:06,735
where we would play mass, mass, mass multiplayer real world games.

92
00:05:06,795 --> 00:05:13,002
So that culminated in a 5,000 player game of basketball in which nobody was hospitalized.

93
00:05:13,243 --> 00:05:15,165
So that's a game design claim to fame.

94
00:05:15,485 --> 00:05:17,426
This is Tiny Games, which some people might just remember.

95
00:05:17,466 --> 00:05:18,726
We kick-started it a few years ago.

96
00:05:19,367 --> 00:05:22,248
This was born out of a series of giant vinyl stickers

97
00:05:22,288 --> 00:05:25,389
that we stuck on sidewalks all over London that kind of gave

98
00:05:25,409 --> 00:05:28,090
you, in a sentence, a game that you could play using

99
00:05:28,110 --> 00:05:29,450
the surroundings immediately around you.

100
00:05:30,671 --> 00:05:33,072
They were a surprisingly big hit on the streets,

101
00:05:33,112 --> 00:05:34,192
so we decided to make them digital.

102
00:05:34,572 --> 00:05:35,893
And then this was just a very simple system

103
00:05:35,993 --> 00:05:37,873
where you could play.

104
00:05:38,634 --> 00:05:41,475
you tell the game where you are, what kind of mood you're in, how many people are there,

105
00:05:41,635 --> 00:05:48,619
if you've got a particular prop that might help, and then the engine serves you the perfect little game that you could play there and then.

106
00:05:50,580 --> 00:05:53,782
Most of these are no longer currently available, which is a thing we can talk about later.

107
00:05:55,003 --> 00:05:57,527
But even before and after that, I was doing a bunch of crazy stuff.

108
00:05:58,108 --> 00:06:00,331
If anyone's interested in any of these, I can tell you more after.

109
00:06:00,371 --> 00:06:01,974
I don't want to bog us down too much in these.

110
00:06:02,434 --> 00:06:06,180
But before I was at Hide and Seek, I was on the team behind Papa Sangre, which was an

111
00:06:06,781 --> 00:06:09,565
iPhone 3D dungeon explorer.

112
00:06:10,326 --> 00:06:12,968
It's a revival game, except with no visuals.

113
00:06:13,168 --> 00:06:15,009
So you had a completely black screen,

114
00:06:15,289 --> 00:06:18,211
and everything about the world was presented

115
00:06:18,251 --> 00:06:20,613
via binaural 3D audio.

116
00:06:20,653 --> 00:06:22,134
So you were navigating by sound alone,

117
00:06:22,154 --> 00:06:24,996
which is an experiment that started out as a question

118
00:06:25,016 --> 00:06:27,217
about whether or not we could make a horror game

119
00:06:27,237 --> 00:06:30,399
that was as accessible to non-sighted players

120
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:31,220
as sighted players.

121
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:36,361
And Drunk Dungeon is a thing I made after I came to New York, which is a game built

122
00:06:36,441 --> 00:06:37,441
out of drinks coasters.

123
00:06:37,541 --> 00:06:39,562
It's designed for a whole party to play together.

124
00:06:39,582 --> 00:06:43,743
You get put into a team when you arrive and then every time you get a drink, you get a

125
00:06:43,783 --> 00:06:47,163
coaster with the drink and the coaster is a play piece that either helps you build out

126
00:06:47,583 --> 00:06:53,144
the dungeon that the game is happening in, or lets you fight battles or move pieces around.

127
00:06:53,604 --> 00:06:58,105
And you have to kind of find the right way to coordinate with every other drunk person

128
00:06:58,965 --> 00:07:01,526
in the bar to figure out how to make that work.

129
00:07:01,826 --> 00:07:04,010
So that, I did that for a long time.

130
00:07:04,951 --> 00:07:06,534
And I'm game director at a company called Dot.

131
00:07:08,046 --> 00:07:08,666
We're in New York.

132
00:07:10,347 --> 00:07:11,527
There's about 50 of us.

133
00:07:12,547 --> 00:07:15,248
One of those is me, but you don't win a prize for figuring out which.

134
00:07:15,808 --> 00:07:16,148
Maybe you do.

135
00:07:16,168 --> 00:07:17,709
It's harder than it looks.

136
00:07:17,729 --> 00:07:19,810
You should check us out.

137
00:07:20,170 --> 00:07:23,471
We're on the internet with that improbably short URL.

138
00:07:24,551 --> 00:07:27,072
We're also on the socials, if you're a fan of the socials.

139
00:07:28,592 --> 00:07:30,193
Our Instagram is particularly pretty.

140
00:07:31,033 --> 00:07:32,653
Recommend our Instagram to you.

141
00:07:33,434 --> 00:07:35,814
And we're called Dots because our first game was this game.

142
00:07:35,994 --> 00:07:36,835
This game is called Dots.

143
00:07:38,483 --> 00:07:39,504
It was about connecting dots.

144
00:07:40,324 --> 00:07:47,351
This kind of came out of a kind of incubator,

145
00:07:47,511 --> 00:07:50,194
skunk worksy thing at a tech startup in New York.

146
00:07:51,775 --> 00:07:53,717
To everyone's surprise, it was a pretty colossal hit.

147
00:07:54,758 --> 00:07:56,740
Got a lot of attention and a lot of players.

148
00:07:57,921 --> 00:07:59,062
And so we followed it up with this game,

149
00:07:59,223 --> 00:08:00,664
which was called Two Dots.

150
00:08:02,025 --> 00:08:07,068
which is exactly the same mechanic but kind of expanded out a little bit bigger

151
00:08:07,868 --> 00:08:11,390
library of game mechanics got into it and much more configured to be a

152
00:08:11,430 --> 00:08:16,213
profitable free-to-play game and then last year we released this game which is

153
00:08:16,253 --> 00:08:16,533
called

154
00:08:17,766 --> 00:08:19,268
Dots and Co, because I wasn't...

155
00:08:20,049 --> 00:08:21,551
I couldn't go with three dots, couldn't do it.

156
00:08:21,912 --> 00:08:23,974
Because when you go next, you can't do four dots.

157
00:08:24,015 --> 00:08:25,977
You've got to call time on it somewhere,

158
00:08:26,017 --> 00:08:26,718
so we call time on it.

159
00:08:27,700 --> 00:08:28,300
And this is what we make.

160
00:08:33,556 --> 00:08:34,636
We're lucky that they're popular,

161
00:08:35,417 --> 00:08:36,477
and that means we make enough money

162
00:08:36,517 --> 00:08:38,077
to have 50 people in New York making them.

163
00:08:39,977 --> 00:08:41,658
But it's obviously pretty different

164
00:08:41,778 --> 00:08:43,698
from where I was spending my time before then.

165
00:08:43,998 --> 00:08:46,218
So I thought I'd pick up on a couple of key areas,

166
00:08:51,119 --> 00:08:53,360
and just poke at that question of what is different

167
00:08:53,380 --> 00:08:55,620
between doing that thing in an indie or house environment

168
00:08:55,640 --> 00:08:57,660
versus a highly commercialized environment.

169
00:08:58,100 --> 00:08:59,721
So, speaking of highly commercialized,

170
00:08:59,741 --> 00:09:00,981
let's start with the money.

171
00:09:02,717 --> 00:09:03,577
And I do start with the money.

172
00:09:03,917 --> 00:09:06,518
This is the first thing I look at every day.

173
00:09:06,538 --> 00:09:11,320
These are our, this is our company-wide KPI email

174
00:09:11,340 --> 00:09:11,940
that comes out every day.

175
00:09:11,980 --> 00:09:12,620
Don't get excited.

176
00:09:13,040 --> 00:09:14,701
I've deleted all of the interesting numbers.

177
00:09:15,281 --> 00:09:17,162
Not sharing anything that should get me into trouble

178
00:09:17,282 --> 00:09:18,222
that I shouldn't be sharing at GDC.

179
00:09:20,864 --> 00:09:21,304
But it's true.

180
00:09:21,404 --> 00:09:23,526
Every day you get up and you look at where those numbers are sitting.

181
00:09:23,926 --> 00:09:27,830
Every single design choice that I make, I'm getting feedback on in terms of the metrics

182
00:09:27,870 --> 00:09:30,692
that our analytics team feedback to me.

183
00:09:32,874 --> 00:09:35,917
I'm very conscious of every decision that I make.

184
00:09:38,198 --> 00:09:40,539
from a production perspective, an artistic perspective,

185
00:09:40,579 --> 00:09:41,439
a game design perspective,

186
00:09:42,039 --> 00:09:44,060
has specific financial ramifications.

187
00:09:45,581 --> 00:09:47,781
And that feels a lot like it comes with the territory,

188
00:09:48,542 --> 00:09:49,882
with being not just in a commercial company,

189
00:09:49,942 --> 00:09:52,943
but a commercial company where you're getting

190
00:09:53,003 --> 00:09:54,464
minute to minute feedback on whether or not

191
00:09:55,204 --> 00:09:56,745
the thing you're doing is hitting the financial targets

192
00:09:56,765 --> 00:09:57,865
that you hope that it will hit.

193
00:09:59,866 --> 00:10:01,767
Except, this is a thing called the COD.

194
00:10:04,095 --> 00:10:05,498
I can't remember why it's called the COD.

195
00:10:05,618 --> 00:10:07,201
No one can remember why it's called the COD,

196
00:10:07,622 --> 00:10:09,325
but it was a thing we used at Hide and Seek

197
00:10:09,706 --> 00:10:13,112
to track all of our spending and all of our income.

198
00:10:13,453 --> 00:10:14,375
This is it.

199
00:10:14,395 --> 00:10:15,557
I haven't hidden any of the numbers here

200
00:10:15,577 --> 00:10:16,960
because there's no exciting numbers to hide.

201
00:10:18,299 --> 00:10:22,642
But you'll see at the top there's some nicely dynamically formatted cells that go pink,

202
00:10:23,303 --> 00:10:24,604
in this case on the 18th of March.

203
00:10:26,005 --> 00:10:30,668
And they go pink because that's our go bus date, as some people would call it.

204
00:10:30,749 --> 00:10:36,533
We tended to call it our go bus date because that's really what it was.

205
00:10:36,713 --> 00:10:38,275
We were a bootstrapped company.

206
00:10:38,395 --> 00:10:39,335
We had no resources.

207
00:10:42,394 --> 00:10:44,697
we could only pay ourselves the next month

208
00:10:44,737 --> 00:10:45,939
if we got paid the previous month.

209
00:10:46,960 --> 00:10:51,086
And especially for the people

210
00:10:51,106 --> 00:10:56,453
you know, who were kind of mostly concerned

211
00:10:56,694 --> 00:10:57,835
with running the company if Humor was won.

212
00:10:59,235 --> 00:11:04,259
it dominated your waking hour to an extent that I could never really articulate at the time.

213
00:11:06,260 --> 00:11:10,964
Because you knew that you couldn't pay rent next month if this didn't happen,

214
00:11:11,004 --> 00:11:14,987
but also that a bunch of people who you adored, who you had lured away from possibly perfectly

215
00:11:15,047 --> 00:11:18,589
successful, sensible person jobs to come and work with you, wouldn't get paid.

216
00:11:18,609 --> 00:11:23,032
And that pressure was super intense. So that pressure was a waking up at two in the morning

217
00:11:23,513 --> 00:11:26,175
intense pressure, not just a rolling out of bed and checking my KPIs.

218
00:11:27,816 --> 00:11:32,357
So the amount of time I spend thinking about money, now that I work for a free-to-play company, is much reduced.

219
00:11:32,778 --> 00:11:39,380
And certainly the amount of energy and friction that I'm dealing with in terms of money is radically reduced.

220
00:11:40,341 --> 00:11:41,181
It's much nicer.

221
00:11:45,022 --> 00:11:50,224
But you saw those screenshots at the beginning.

222
00:11:51,460 --> 00:11:56,244
seems like a fair question to ask whether or not that has come at the expense of abandoning

223
00:11:56,445 --> 00:11:58,646
interesting, unpredictable work for...

224
00:12:00,748 --> 00:12:00,988
I mean...

225
00:12:01,008 --> 00:12:06,493
I don't want to say boring, but you can see how similar those three screenshots are to each other.

226
00:12:06,513 --> 00:12:08,355
This is the same game three times.

227
00:12:09,055 --> 00:12:09,636
And that's what I do.

228
00:12:12,478 --> 00:12:12,778
And...

229
00:12:13,979 --> 00:12:15,481
What I found is...

230
00:12:15,861 --> 00:12:16,982
a thing I wasn't expecting to find.

231
00:12:17,602 --> 00:12:17,983
So these are...

232
00:12:20,065 --> 00:12:21,006
Don't worry, they don't make sense.

233
00:12:21,867 --> 00:12:26,449
These are early prototypes for the last new puzzle mechanic

234
00:12:26,469 --> 00:12:27,810
we introduced in two dots.

235
00:12:28,811 --> 00:12:29,611
They're called paddles.

236
00:12:31,573 --> 00:12:36,336
The kind of idea here is that if you clear dots along,

237
00:12:36,636 --> 00:12:40,798
so they're a set of tiles that function together.

238
00:12:40,818 --> 00:12:42,319
Along one side is a hinge.

239
00:12:42,379 --> 00:12:44,521
If you clear dots along the hinge, then they flip,

240
00:12:44,661 --> 00:12:46,062
and then whatever they land on, they squish.

241
00:12:47,403 --> 00:12:49,824
And then if you clear dots on the other side of the hinge,

242
00:12:49,844 --> 00:12:50,465
then they flip back.

243
00:12:50,965 --> 00:12:52,886
And while they're not flipping,

