00:38:49,619 --> 00:38:50,520
from the people that we shared it to

735
00:38:50,620 --> 00:38:51,700
because they felt like they were getting

736
00:38:51,720 --> 00:38:52,340
something meaningful.

737
00:38:52,801 --> 00:38:55,182
We also, this was a collaboration with Ryan and Kennedy,

738
00:38:55,362 --> 00:38:57,003
and they had a super cute idea

739
00:38:57,883 --> 00:38:59,184
that if you tried to circumvent that

740
00:38:59,244 --> 00:39:00,484
and share it more widely,

741
00:39:01,125 --> 00:39:02,926
it showed up on your Facebook feed as redacted.

742
00:39:03,725 --> 00:39:07,289
So you could share the URL, but everything showed up with a text blacked out.

743
00:39:07,309 --> 00:39:08,390
It looked super cool.

744
00:39:10,091 --> 00:39:14,155
So we just said, no, you don't, you have to, one person, pick one person.

745
00:39:14,235 --> 00:39:15,276
And it worked so well.

746
00:39:15,376 --> 00:39:18,579
I know I never would have done it if I hadn't made a bunch of real-world social games

747
00:39:18,619 --> 00:39:19,960
that operate kind of very differently.

748
00:39:20,161 --> 00:39:22,603
So that still feels different and better.

749
00:39:22,623 --> 00:39:23,744
That's that.

750
00:39:24,465 --> 00:39:24,785
And then...

751
00:39:27,502 --> 00:39:34,249
When I started out working in games and as a game designer, I'd come up as a game journalist and a game designer,

752
00:39:34,790 --> 00:39:37,413
and if you asked me to express myself, I would write you an essay.

753
00:39:37,733 --> 00:39:42,298
I would do a nice design document, with headings, and that's what you would get.

754
00:39:43,340 --> 00:39:48,042
And I went from that to being smashed into a room with people from Widen and Kennedy,

755
00:39:48,162 --> 00:39:53,104
or RGA, or Mother, or whatever else, or people from Tate Modern, or Royal Opera House.

756
00:39:53,644 --> 00:39:56,505
The expectation of your ability to communicate visually,

757
00:39:57,105 --> 00:40:00,246
and the expectation of your ability to present your ideas

758
00:40:00,266 --> 00:40:04,088
kind of to the best of their capabilities,

759
00:40:05,308 --> 00:40:07,669
was a lot of pressure very fast.

760
00:40:07,789 --> 00:40:10,110
And I mean, you guys are...

761
00:40:12,579 --> 00:40:17,604
going to be the judge of it, but I'm hoping that I'm a little bit better at presenting

762
00:40:17,824 --> 00:40:22,589
my ideas than I was when I started out with those endless Word documents.

763
00:40:24,371 --> 00:40:27,294
So I'm contractually obliged to give you takeaways.

764
00:40:27,314 --> 00:40:29,716
I think I might actually be contractually obliged to give you takeaways.

765
00:40:29,736 --> 00:40:31,978
That joke doesn't work in America, does it?

766
00:40:31,998 --> 00:40:35,482
Have we got any Brits who can give me a takeaway laugh?

767
00:40:35,502 --> 00:40:35,542
No?

768
00:40:35,782 --> 00:40:36,303
All right.

769
00:40:37,406 --> 00:40:39,330
You're lucky you didn't get a picture of a munchie box, which

770
00:40:40,072 --> 00:40:43,460
sounds like you shouldn't Google, but you can Google, but then you'll still kind of wish you hadn't Googled.

771
00:40:44,422 --> 00:40:44,662
Um...

772
00:40:46,286 --> 00:40:47,148
So I try to think about...

773
00:40:51,073 --> 00:40:54,233
Can I give any advice that's actually real useful advice

774
00:40:54,253 --> 00:40:56,834
and advice that I can imagine myself having followed

775
00:40:56,854 --> 00:40:59,975
either at the indie studio when I was helping run that

776
00:41:00,055 --> 00:41:02,176
or at the commercial studio that I'm helping run now?

777
00:41:03,616 --> 00:41:04,897
And I decided that in both cases,

778
00:41:06,517 --> 00:41:11,138
it's all about the three Fs.

779
00:41:11,218 --> 00:41:15,800
I'm lucky to be in the studio that I'm at now

780
00:41:16,660 --> 00:41:17,920
and a big part of...

781
00:41:20,160 --> 00:41:22,003
What's enabled that is just the people that we have.

782
00:41:22,284 --> 00:41:23,686
We have a weird mix of people,

783
00:41:24,287 --> 00:41:26,251
and we are very unprejudicial

784
00:41:26,391 --> 00:41:28,094
about what people's backgrounds are.

785
00:41:28,976 --> 00:41:30,358
We don't care about experience,

786
00:41:30,498 --> 00:41:32,462
and we don't care about industry background.

787
00:41:33,677 --> 00:41:38,781
What we do care about, or certainly what I care about when I'm looking to hire game designers,

788
00:41:39,761 --> 00:41:41,223
is that kind of fundamental fluency.

789
00:41:41,463 --> 00:41:45,906
Are you fast? Are you used to having to undergo a bunch of playtesting?

790
00:41:46,006 --> 00:41:47,688
Are you good at taking that kind of feedback?

791
00:41:48,088 --> 00:41:51,331
Are you good at communicating your ideas effectively and visually to a team?

792
00:41:51,551 --> 00:41:53,392
I do not care how you've come by that experience.

793
00:41:53,412 --> 00:41:55,254
I don't care whether you've got a degree. I don't care.

794
00:41:55,834 --> 00:41:59,877
I don't care if you do have experience and you're bringing it to me out of a free-to-play studio,

795
00:42:00,217 --> 00:42:01,998
I don't care if it's a bunch of game jams that you've done,

796
00:42:02,418 --> 00:42:07,742
I don't care if it's some skills that you can transfer across from having been working in advertising or whatever else,

797
00:42:07,762 --> 00:42:11,604
I don't care. If I feel like you can do it, that's my number one concern.

798
00:42:13,826 --> 00:42:17,768
I do care a bit about your degree of familiarity with the space that I'm in.

799
00:42:18,028 --> 00:42:20,890
Free-to-play has a bunch of weird habits and...

800
00:42:24,418 --> 00:42:26,360
best practices that it's very useful to know,

801
00:42:26,420 --> 00:42:29,423
but I don't care whether you know them

802
00:42:29,463 --> 00:42:30,604
as a player or a designer.

803
00:42:31,565 --> 00:42:34,888
If you have some degree of fluency with what that takes,

804
00:42:37,811 --> 00:42:39,292
or how that works and how it fits together,

805
00:42:39,312 --> 00:42:43,696
then that's all you need to make it on my list.

806
00:42:44,117 --> 00:42:45,698
And then the third F is experience.

807
00:42:48,700 --> 00:42:55,344
Because it helps, you know, I think that thing that I talked about earlier in terms of knowing what it takes to take something over the line does matter.

808
00:42:55,544 --> 00:43:10,553
Knowing, you know, there is an amount of grit and a kind of breadth of focus that you need as you come to the end of a project to make sure that it debuts fulfilling all of the hopes that you had for it.

809
00:43:11,153 --> 00:43:14,575
But again, I don't necessarily care about whether or not that's strictly speaking in games.

810
00:43:14,615 --> 00:43:14,996
And I think...

811
00:43:20,245 --> 00:43:24,531
The value for doing that is there's a different talk I could have been giving today.

812
00:43:24,571 --> 00:43:28,998
If I was at a different studio, I wouldn't have been able to say so many of the nice things that I said about,

813
00:43:29,078 --> 00:43:32,362
oh, hey, we did this ACLU thing, or hey, we got to do this artist collaboration.

814
00:43:32,402 --> 00:43:35,046
I know that not everybody who's working in free-to-play is in that sphere.

815
00:43:36,067 --> 00:43:36,248
But...

816
00:43:37,087 --> 00:43:39,308
In a successful business, there just is the scope.

817
00:43:39,648 --> 00:43:45,410
I know that from being in a absolutely down to the bones, impoverished indie studio.

818
00:43:46,071 --> 00:43:48,212
We never had the scope to do those kind of things.

819
00:43:48,252 --> 00:43:51,953
And in a bigger studio, you can if there is the institutional will.

820
00:43:51,973 --> 00:43:54,875
And the institutional will is built out of the people who make up the studio.

821
00:43:55,455 --> 00:43:58,277
And so the more you bring in people who are gonna help you

822
00:43:58,317 --> 00:44:00,959
stay connected to a wider cultural sphere

823
00:44:00,979 --> 00:44:04,721
and a more diverse set of attitudes and beliefs,

824
00:44:05,162 --> 00:44:07,263
the more it becomes credible that you can start to

825
00:44:07,804 --> 00:44:10,165
kind of incubate those kinds of projects and activities

826
00:44:10,205 --> 00:44:11,646
within that commercial environment.

827
00:44:11,666 --> 00:44:13,548
For any of these, it's also the three Fs.

828
00:44:14,789 --> 00:44:16,270
Actually, or three Fs this time.

829
00:44:17,411 --> 00:44:18,211
Last year, I made a sequel.

830
00:44:18,371 --> 00:44:19,812
I made Dots and Co, it's a sequel to Two Dots.

831
00:44:20,393 --> 00:44:22,194
It was unbelievably hard.

832
00:44:23,914 --> 00:44:25,894
So hard, kinda hated it.

833
00:44:26,614 --> 00:44:28,415
Learned so much, super proud of it.

834
00:44:29,976 --> 00:44:31,136
I never did that as an indie.

835
00:44:31,156 --> 00:44:32,997
You never make a sequel as an indie, are you crazy?

836
00:44:33,557 --> 00:44:36,278
You're lucky if you survive releasing anything once ever,

837
00:44:36,518 --> 00:44:37,858
and then even if you make it that far,

838
00:44:37,878 --> 00:44:39,659
you probably have to do something different the next time.

839
00:44:40,399 --> 00:44:43,901
And so the design education I got

840
00:44:44,101 --> 00:44:45,981
out of really, really tearing down,

841
00:44:46,922 --> 00:44:50,024
an existing successful game. It was such a hard challenge because it

842
00:44:50,784 --> 00:44:53,186
often when you make a sequel you made a game and you released it and it did or

843
00:44:53,226 --> 00:44:56,008
didn't do okay and then time passed and now you're going to make another version

844
00:44:56,048 --> 00:44:58,569
of it. That's cool. In the modern games and

845
00:44:58,589 --> 00:45:00,270
services age that's not how it works. Two Dots

846
00:45:01,651 --> 00:45:04,453
isn't going anywhere. It's wildly successful.

847
00:45:04,813 --> 00:45:08,576
It's iterating incredibly fast. Month on month on month it gets better and cooler

848
00:45:08,936 --> 00:45:11,738
and grander. Coming in on top of that to say well

849
00:45:11,778 --> 00:45:14,200
how do I make a sister game that sits next to that meaningfully?

850
00:45:16,151 --> 00:45:18,512
meant I had to go through a process of deconstructing

851
00:45:18,572 --> 00:45:20,113
all of the stuff about how 2Dots works,

852
00:45:20,153 --> 00:45:21,054
but also where it's going,

853
00:45:21,454 --> 00:45:22,814
but also where this could go that's different.

854
00:45:23,095 --> 00:45:24,855
It was just like no design challenge I'd ever had.

855
00:45:25,356 --> 00:45:30,798
So, I exhort anybody out there

856
00:45:30,818 --> 00:45:32,499
who's working in an indie or art house space

857
00:45:33,760 --> 00:45:35,401
to see if they can find a way to make a follow-up.

858
00:45:36,361 --> 00:45:38,022
Now, I know that's not necessarily simple.

859
00:45:38,082 --> 00:45:39,663
I know enough about being an indie

860
00:45:39,683 --> 00:45:41,064
to know you don't always get an awful lot of choice

861
00:45:41,104 --> 00:45:41,804
about what you do next.

862
00:45:42,344 --> 00:45:43,905
If you can't make a follow-up for real,

863
00:45:44,626 --> 00:45:45,526
And just pretend.

864
00:45:46,107 --> 00:45:47,007
Just do a thought experiment.

865
00:45:47,027 --> 00:45:49,509
Just sit down with a thing that you made six months ago.

866
00:45:49,650 --> 00:45:52,372
It's a very different process than doing a post-mortem.

867
00:45:52,992 --> 00:45:54,453
Go back to a thing that was finished

868
00:45:54,834 --> 00:45:57,556
and imagine that you were gonna do a sequel to it.

869
00:45:57,576 --> 00:45:58,717
You were gonna release a new version of it

870
00:45:58,877 --> 00:46:00,598
three months, six months, a year from now,

871
00:46:01,379 --> 00:46:02,339
and see what it teaches you.

872
00:46:06,427 --> 00:46:13,112
Yeah, because you may not realize that there's a whole kind of design thinking that you're never confronting

873
00:46:14,173 --> 00:46:16,554
if you're working in a way that's more free-form and independent.

874
00:46:17,355 --> 00:46:20,938
And then this is maybe one of the toughest takeaways for me.

875
00:46:21,998 --> 00:46:24,520
I loved working independently, I loved the crazy things that I got to do.

876
00:46:25,421 --> 00:46:29,404
But I'm seeing now what being at a more focused studio is enabling me to do.

877
00:46:31,810 --> 00:46:33,411
you know, reveling in that opportunity.

878
00:46:34,372 --> 00:46:35,692
Alex Fleetwood, who isn't here,

879
00:46:36,833 --> 00:46:37,994
my business partner in Hide and Seek,

880
00:46:38,754 --> 00:46:40,675
in the time, we shut out Hide and Seek

881
00:46:42,156 --> 00:46:43,697
three years ago, I think, maybe three and a bit.

882
00:46:43,717 --> 00:46:46,118
In the time since then, he's caught his breath

883
00:46:46,158 --> 00:46:48,439
and then come back with a project that was inspired by

884
00:46:48,459 --> 00:46:50,940
a very, very, very embryonic project we did at Hide and Seek

885
00:46:50,980 --> 00:46:52,161
maybe six or seven years ago.

886
00:46:52,181 --> 00:46:54,862
And he's spent...

887
00:46:57,653 --> 00:47:00,075
two and a bit years, and is now focusing energy

888
00:47:00,115 --> 00:47:02,597
of five or six people, and one thing and one thing only,

889
00:47:02,637 --> 00:47:05,478
which is this, this is Beast of Balance, his new game.

890
00:47:06,639 --> 00:47:10,021
He's been, he showed it at the last two GDCs,

891
00:47:10,161 --> 00:47:12,903
he just told me earlier, today was the first time,

892
00:47:13,183 --> 00:47:16,265
this GDC was the first time where he came to show the game,

893
00:47:16,305 --> 00:47:17,626
instead of having to bring it in a suitcase,

894
00:47:18,166 --> 00:47:20,207
when he got to San Francisco, he just went to the store,

895
00:47:20,307 --> 00:47:22,089
and he bought a copy of it in the store,

896
00:47:22,249 --> 00:47:23,149
and then brought it to the thing,

897
00:47:23,229 --> 00:47:24,770
and it's a great and proud moment.

898
00:47:25,391 --> 00:47:26,671
And I look at that, and,

899
00:47:28,869 --> 00:47:29,869
It looks to me like two things.

900
00:47:29,929 --> 00:47:32,229
It looks to me like a thing we could have made at Hide and Seek.

901
00:47:32,389 --> 00:47:33,169
It's so much.

902
00:47:33,189 --> 00:47:33,770
You should check it out.

903
00:47:33,790 --> 00:47:35,010
It's super cool and crazy and weird.

904
00:47:35,330 --> 00:47:37,050
It's so much the kind of thing we love to make there.

905
00:47:37,430 --> 00:47:42,771
It's like one part game, one part poem, one part educational app,

906
00:47:42,931 --> 00:47:44,872
one part sculpture.

907
00:47:46,132 --> 00:47:48,352
It's exactly the kind of thing that we love to do.

908
00:47:48,732 --> 00:47:50,053
And it's also exactly the kind of thing

909
00:47:50,073 --> 00:47:51,933
that we would never have accomplished.

910
00:47:52,053 --> 00:47:55,294
Because the way you do this is you do nothing else for two years.

911
00:47:57,174 --> 00:47:57,714
And I think.

912
00:48:00,910 --> 00:48:03,312
If I had it all to do again, I think as an indie,

913
00:48:03,852 --> 00:48:07,114
we got bounced so much into trying to do everything

914
00:48:07,134 --> 00:48:08,515
because we never wanted to turn anything down

915
00:48:08,535 --> 00:48:09,676
and we never had the confidence

916
00:48:10,056 --> 00:48:11,357
to just try and pick one thing.

917
00:48:12,338 --> 00:48:15,120
And I do now really wonder what, you know,

918
00:48:15,860 --> 00:48:16,901
some of those ideas I showed at the beginning

919
00:48:16,921 --> 00:48:19,042
were cute ideas, that board game remix kit was a cute idea,

920
00:48:19,082 --> 00:48:20,203
Tiny Games was a cute idea.

921
00:48:21,024 --> 00:48:23,105
But we put this much focus into it

922
00:48:23,205 --> 00:48:25,607
and then had to transfer it to something else.

923
00:48:25,787 --> 00:48:26,207
And I think,

924
00:48:28,835 --> 00:48:34,040
I think if I've learned anything moving into the commercial world,

925
00:48:34,080 --> 00:48:36,702
actually, it's not about following the money,

926
00:48:36,762 --> 00:48:38,244
and it's not about worrying about the margins,

927
00:48:38,284 --> 00:48:42,607
but it's about what a commercial,

928
00:48:42,948 --> 00:48:46,991
the focus that a commercial structure can enable

929
00:48:48,713 --> 00:48:50,074
that you struggle to get elsewhere.

930
00:48:50,094 --> 00:48:53,737
Because that's really the thing, this, I opened with this,

931
00:48:53,897 --> 00:48:56,740
this is Uncle Death, any Uncle Death fans?

932
00:48:58,627 --> 00:49:00,028
I can't see you, but there you go.

933
00:49:00,048 --> 00:49:02,408
So this is Uncle Death, he's your,

934
00:49:04,269 --> 00:49:05,809
I don't know what he is, he's your mentor,

935
00:49:05,849 --> 00:49:07,370
he's your bully, he's your something or other

936
00:49:07,450 --> 00:49:13,012
in Let It Die, which is Suda51's weird,

937
00:49:14,392 --> 00:49:19,233
free-to-play console brawler.

938
00:49:23,510 --> 00:49:24,351
And that's interesting because...

939
00:49:25,632 --> 00:49:28,916
I mean, I picked him just because he was my favorite Grim Reaper I could find in games.

940
00:49:28,936 --> 00:49:32,059
I try to find good devils in games, and it's a weird space.

941
00:49:32,699 --> 00:49:37,564
Once you decide you don't want to do a Diablo thing, you don't know what else you're going to do.

942
00:49:37,684 --> 00:49:38,965
His site's a golf club.

943
00:49:38,985 --> 00:49:44,330
But yeah, so I picked him because he's cool.

944
00:49:44,671 --> 00:49:46,953
But also, I mean, there is somebody who has...

945
00:49:48,267 --> 00:49:52,529
whose career has taken him from making things that are very much on the margins

946
00:49:52,589 --> 00:49:57,151
and very much kind of creatively auteur-style defined and delivered,

947
00:49:57,612 --> 00:50:00,073
through to a point where, you know, I make free-to-play games,

948
00:50:00,093 --> 00:50:02,254
and he makes free-to-play games now, and they're pretty different,

949
00:50:02,394 --> 00:50:05,356
and, you know, we have nothing to do with each other,

950
00:50:05,476 --> 00:50:07,917
but it seemed like an interesting end.

951
00:50:08,017 --> 00:50:11,099
But, so he's a cute choice of Grim Reaper, but he's not really appropriate,

952
00:50:11,119 --> 00:50:14,621
because this is more about rebirth, I think.

953
00:50:14,861 --> 00:50:16,742
We work in a super volatile industry.

954
00:50:16,862 --> 00:50:17,162
I don't...

955
00:50:18,193 --> 00:50:21,396
There's probably nobody here, or functionally nobody here,

956
00:50:21,416 --> 00:50:24,620
who's been cozy and happy in the same company

957
00:50:24,700 --> 00:50:26,802
for the last 25 years making the same kind of games.

958
00:50:26,863 --> 00:50:29,065
That's not how it works for us.

959
00:50:29,646 --> 00:50:32,609
There's too many winds of change blowing around.

960
00:50:33,390 --> 00:50:36,571
games. It's part of what we love about games. The technology changes or the business model changes

961
00:50:37,352 --> 00:50:43,214
or the audience changes or we uncover some kind of new control mechanism or new paradigm.

962
00:50:44,175 --> 00:50:49,457
We're all dodging all of your stuff out there right now. It's never going to let us rest easy.

963
00:50:50,237 --> 00:50:56,580
And so for me the biggest thing I've learned in this transition is those fundamentals, that kind

964
00:50:56,600 --> 00:51:01,683
of the work is the work core practice stuff, comes with you. Like even if everything else

965
00:51:02,783 --> 00:51:07,424
falls apart and we, Hide and Seek had an elegant end.

966
00:51:08,224 --> 00:51:09,484
We never hit that go bust date,

967
00:51:10,484 --> 00:51:12,885
despite the fact it tried its best.

968
00:51:13,665 --> 00:51:15,825
And we were able to find the right moment to say,

969
00:51:15,925 --> 00:51:19,186
this isn't gonna work anymore and finish our projects,

970
00:51:19,226 --> 00:51:20,046
close things down elegantly,

971
00:51:20,086 --> 00:51:22,247
treat everybody who worked there, I hope well.

972
00:51:22,687 --> 00:51:23,807
We believe that we did that well.

973
00:51:25,207 --> 00:51:27,208
Still felt god awful.

974
00:51:27,288 --> 00:51:31,228
It felt absolutely excruciatingly miserable.

975
00:51:32,356 --> 00:51:37,119
And I know that I'm not necessarily safe from that again in the future.

976
00:51:37,139 --> 00:51:41,202
Right now I'm at a happy, successful company that all our expectations are,

977
00:51:41,242 --> 00:51:44,665
we'll continue to be happy and successful, but I've done this long enough to know that,

978
00:51:45,185 --> 00:51:47,547
you know, there are fates that await game companies.

979
00:51:47,587 --> 00:51:53,231
They get bought by less friendly game companies, or their fourth sequel doesn't do as well,

980
00:51:53,251 --> 00:51:56,213
or they back the wrong horse in terms of a technology platform,

981
00:51:56,253 --> 00:51:57,934
or an input mechanism, or whatever it is.

982
00:51:59,630 --> 00:52:07,094
So I probably won't be here forever either, but now I've got a clearer sense of how translatable

983
00:52:07,635 --> 00:52:10,516
the skills that I have are, not necessarily to different industries, but just to different places

984
00:52:10,596 --> 00:52:15,159
within the same industry. And I think we'll do better if we recognize that in each other,

985
00:52:15,179 --> 00:52:21,382
that rather than just ending up with a much more kind of closed circle where indies know how to

986
00:52:21,402 --> 00:52:24,744
talk to indies but are skeptical about people who've come from a free-to-play background,

987
00:52:25,124 --> 00:52:25,904
or vice versa, we...

988
00:52:28,206 --> 00:52:30,828
recognize that there are fundamental capabilities

989
00:52:30,848 --> 00:52:32,950
that transcend those categories.

990
00:52:34,592 --> 00:52:36,574
That is what I have for you.

991
00:52:38,116 --> 00:52:38,676
We're hiring.

992
00:52:40,678 --> 00:52:42,540
That's it, you're done, GDC's over!

993
00:52:57,935 --> 00:52:59,516
Your questions are welcome.

994
00:53:01,097 --> 00:53:05,479
So the topic that was most interesting to me about the

995
00:53:05,519 --> 00:53:08,181
transition, a lot of what you're describing to me feels

996
00:53:08,221 --> 00:53:10,883
like going from a consulting environment in some ways,

997
00:53:10,903 --> 00:53:13,144
because you're also doing projects for these corporate

998
00:53:13,164 --> 00:53:13,545
clients.

999
00:53:14,742 --> 00:53:18,566
Going to free-to-play, the thing that has struck me,

1000
00:53:18,947 --> 00:53:21,049
like coming to GDC over the last five years,

1001
00:53:21,530 --> 00:53:23,952
was there was a lot of discussion about free-to-play

1002
00:53:24,132 --> 00:53:28,377
where it was whales and it's about paywalls

1003
00:53:28,817 --> 00:53:33,542
and ads and offers and skinner boxes, frankly,

1004
00:53:33,803 --> 00:53:35,765
where it felt very skeevy to me.

1005
00:53:36,405 --> 00:53:39,227
So for me, when I'm thinking about free-to-play,

1006
00:53:39,787 --> 00:53:42,528
that's the part that creeps me out, to be perfectly honest,

1007
00:53:42,649 --> 00:53:43,009
is that.

1008
00:53:44,189 --> 00:53:47,571
Obviously, Dots has a model.

1009
00:53:48,892 --> 00:53:52,153
How much does that influence your design work,

1010
00:53:52,213 --> 00:53:55,315
how you feel about what you do, when you look at free-to-play

1011
00:53:55,355 --> 00:53:56,515
and what you associate with?

1012
00:53:57,256 --> 00:53:59,697
So it's sort of a broad question.

1013
00:53:59,757 --> 00:54:00,197
No, I got it.

1014
00:54:00,237 --> 00:54:00,397
Got it.

1015
00:54:07,634 --> 00:54:12,858
I, what's, DODS is a very classic free-to-play approach.

1016
00:54:14,339 --> 00:54:16,701
And a thing that makes my life very easy

1017
00:54:16,841 --> 00:54:20,203
is that we don't, we don't do anything

1018
00:54:20,243 --> 00:54:23,446
we would be uncomfortable if our players knew about.

1019
00:54:23,466 --> 00:54:27,209
That's kind of our litmus is, would we feel okay

1020
00:54:27,369 --> 00:54:29,270
about if someone who loved our game came in

1021
00:54:29,331 --> 00:54:30,331
and said, how does this work?

1022
00:54:30,371 --> 00:54:31,913
And we went, oh, well, it's like this.

1023
00:54:32,753 --> 00:54:36,116
Would they feel like we'd been tricking them?

1024
00:54:37,096 --> 00:54:39,037
There's a couple things that we're not super public about

1025
00:54:39,077 --> 00:54:40,718
just because they're complicated,

1026
00:54:41,599 --> 00:54:44,261
but we'd very happily talk anyone through them at length.

1027
00:54:44,301 --> 00:54:45,441
It's just hard to put it in a tweet

1028
00:54:45,501 --> 00:54:48,063
in a way that won't misconstrue.

1029
00:54:48,203 --> 00:54:50,424
There's like a bunch of like super dense

1030
00:54:50,504 --> 00:54:51,865
spawning rules around objects

1031
00:54:51,885 --> 00:54:53,386
to make sure that the games stay fun

1032
00:54:53,446 --> 00:54:54,867
even when players do weird things.

1033
00:54:55,027 --> 00:54:56,608
And so those are hard to explain,

1034
00:54:56,648 --> 00:54:58,970
but they're designed only to make sure

1035
00:54:59,010 --> 00:55:00,871
people continue to have happy game experiences.

1036
00:55:00,891 --> 00:55:02,752
They're not revenue focused.

1037
00:55:08,431 --> 00:55:12,614
It's weird. I've made games that are just supposed to be about joy.

1038
00:55:13,575 --> 00:55:16,277
I've made games that are in a consulting or educational environment

1039
00:55:16,397 --> 00:55:21,781
where you're taking people to a point where there's some kind of threshold

1040
00:55:21,822 --> 00:55:25,945
you have to cross. Where they have to learn a thing or do a thing.

1041
00:55:26,725 --> 00:55:30,909
Sometimes that thing is they have to click on a link to go to the Green Lantern trailer.

1042
00:55:31,489 --> 00:55:34,031
And sometimes they have to prove that they've learned a Greek verb

1043
00:55:34,051 --> 00:55:37,094
or sometimes whatever they are. And now I'm in this place where...

1044
00:55:38,995 --> 00:55:41,997
We have a sumptuous, expensive game that we give away for free,

1045
00:55:42,117 --> 00:55:44,119
and then we get people to a point where we say,

1046
00:55:44,139 --> 00:55:48,143
if you want to keep going right now, you need to put your hand in your pocket.

1047
00:55:49,296 --> 00:55:52,537
And those things just feel super identical to me.

1048
00:55:52,817 --> 00:55:55,218
Like it's definitely not harder or weirder

1049
00:55:55,238 --> 00:55:57,099
to get somebody to give me a dollar

1050
00:55:57,199 --> 00:55:58,940
than it is to get them to watch the Green Lantern trailer.

1051
00:55:59,820 --> 00:56:03,041
And it's actually not that different.

1052
00:56:03,161 --> 00:56:04,522
In fact, maybe quite a lot easier

1053
00:56:04,702 --> 00:56:06,823
than when I'm designing a street game for Edinburgh,

1054
00:56:06,983 --> 00:56:10,184
where what I'm trying to construct

1055
00:56:10,684 --> 00:56:11,885
is a set of gaming incentives

1056
00:56:11,905 --> 00:56:14,426
where you will go and hold the hand of a stranger.

1057
00:56:15,736 --> 00:56:20,120
And frankly, if you give me the design challenge to make you give me a dollar,

1058
00:56:20,480 --> 00:56:23,142
versus the one where you have to hold hands with a stranger, I'll take the dollar, right?

1059
00:56:23,162 --> 00:56:24,163
That's easier.

1060
00:56:24,943 --> 00:56:29,667
So I think that the design challenge doesn't feel any different.

1061
00:56:29,867 --> 00:56:30,248
It's about...

1062
00:56:33,174 --> 00:56:35,255
motivating your player and then restricting the resources

1063
00:56:35,275 --> 00:56:36,775
that they have to reach the thing that you've motivated

1064
00:56:36,815 --> 00:56:38,716
them to reach, and then giving them interesting options

1065
00:56:39,456 --> 00:56:42,377
to resolve that restriction, and then spending

1066
00:56:42,437 --> 00:56:44,418
is one of them, but you're always gonna wanna offer

1067
00:56:44,438 --> 00:56:47,639
your player that choice anyway, and so it's just

1068
00:56:47,679 --> 00:56:49,079
what you swap in and out of those categories.

1069
00:56:49,119 --> 00:56:50,640
That doesn't, it just feels exactly the same.

1070
00:56:51,100 --> 00:56:53,221
Where it would feel different is if there was stuff

1071
00:56:53,241 --> 00:56:55,582
that I thought was exploitative or underhanded,

1072
00:56:56,162 --> 00:56:58,723
or designed to mislead or trick people.

1073
00:57:00,083 --> 00:57:02,824
We just don't have any of that, so it seems easy.

1074
00:57:04,080 --> 00:57:05,301
Is that at all helpful?

1075
00:57:05,601 --> 00:57:09,084
Yeah, I think if I was going to try to replay it,

1076
00:57:09,424 --> 00:57:11,445
the real core is, as long as you're

1077
00:57:11,465 --> 00:57:14,088
transparent with the users and you

1078
00:57:14,108 --> 00:57:17,330
feel ethical about what you're producing, it's OK.

1079
00:57:17,971 --> 00:57:20,312
And that might be part of that design process,

1080
00:57:20,392 --> 00:57:22,674
too, about where do you put in your loops

1081
00:57:22,754 --> 00:57:23,975
and how do you construct them?

1082
00:57:24,075 --> 00:57:25,696
Are these things feeling ethical or not?

1083
00:57:25,997 --> 00:57:28,719
If you feel good about it, then, well, you can sleep at night.

1084
00:57:29,527 --> 00:57:31,809
That's kind of what I think I'm hearing.

1085
00:57:32,029 --> 00:57:32,709
I think that's right.

1086
00:57:34,050 --> 00:57:36,631
That doesn't feel at all controversial to me.

1087
00:57:37,252 --> 00:57:41,114
And I think some of it definitely comes from designing face-to-face with players.

1088
00:57:42,455 --> 00:57:49,359
The model that I always have in my head is that an individual human is going to want to sit down and ask me questions

1089
00:57:49,919 --> 00:57:51,800
about any design choice that I make.

1090
00:57:54,866 --> 00:57:56,888
Yeah, it kind of just makes it trivially easy.

1091
00:57:56,928 --> 00:57:59,150
It's like, do I know how to answer that person's questions?

1092
00:57:59,731 --> 00:58:00,732
Cool, then I'm doing the right thing.

1093
00:58:00,832 --> 00:58:03,114
If I'm uncomfortable, then we do something else.

1094
00:58:03,134 --> 00:58:03,575
It's easy.

1095
00:58:03,615 --> 00:58:06,117
Yeah, that's helpful, because that also will allow me to,

1096
00:58:06,177 --> 00:58:07,559
one of the things I'm struggling,

1097
00:58:07,579 --> 00:58:08,900
I'm sorry, you guys have a question,

1098
00:58:09,320 --> 00:58:12,704
is how do I test out my monetization strategy?

1099
00:58:13,044 --> 00:58:15,386
And so if I can sit with somebody and face-to-face and.

1100
00:58:16,119 --> 00:58:18,721
know that they're going to say, okay, well, no, that's skewier, that's good.

1101
00:58:18,741 --> 00:58:19,962
That also gives me a design.

1102
00:58:20,102 --> 00:58:23,204
Well, I do, I, I, I pen and paper test all my monetization stuff.

1103
00:58:23,545 --> 00:58:26,267
Well, I pen and money test all my monetization stuff.

1104
00:58:26,307 --> 00:58:30,990
I have a cup of dollar bills on my desk and, and tokens and

1105
00:58:31,230 --> 00:58:32,131
everything gets tested like that.

1106
00:58:32,771 --> 00:58:32,951
Okay.

1107
00:58:32,971 --> 00:58:33,172
Thank you.

1108
00:58:35,165 --> 00:58:35,345
Hi.

1109
00:58:36,005 --> 00:58:37,846
So there was another talk today.

1110
00:58:38,607 --> 00:58:41,569
There's a researcher who is surveying game designers

1111
00:58:41,769 --> 00:58:44,871
to get their definition of success.

1112
00:58:46,732 --> 00:58:49,694
So what's your definition of success,

1113
00:58:49,774 --> 00:58:54,377
and did it change when you moved from one studio to the other?

1114
00:59:00,257 --> 00:59:01,217
You didn't have to answer.

1115
00:59:01,237 --> 00:59:03,058
Um, yeah, I've...

1116
00:59:03,078 --> 00:59:06,259
I have so far been 100% unsuccessful, I would say.

1117
00:59:07,079 --> 00:59:10,720
I've never, like, I feel like I'd maybe be successful if I

1118
00:59:12,141 --> 00:59:14,781
made a thing that I felt was good and that I was proud of.

1119
00:59:14,801 --> 00:59:16,402
I don't really feel like that.

1120
00:59:16,982 --> 00:59:20,123
Everything is full of compromises and missed opportunities.

1121
00:59:20,763 --> 00:59:22,204
The games that I love...

1122
00:59:23,322 --> 00:59:28,244
have a essentialism about them that you know that you couldn't, you can't change a single

1123
00:59:28,304 --> 00:59:36,348
rule of that game because it's just right, it's just perfect. And I'm fascinated by those games

1124
00:59:36,928 --> 00:59:42,971
and in all of them and I know I've not come close to making anything that good. So there's like,

1125
00:59:42,991 --> 00:59:48,153
I guess, yeah, I guess I have two definitions of success. There's that one which I haven't hit and

1126
00:59:48,173 --> 00:59:48,753
maybe I'll never hit.

1127
00:59:49,600 --> 00:59:50,020
Keep trying.

1128
00:59:50,681 --> 00:59:53,521
And the other one is, oh my god, I make games for a living.

1129
00:59:54,782 --> 00:59:57,922
Any year where I can pull that together is a success.

1130
00:59:58,722 --> 01:00:00,683
And I've done it for 10, and maybe I'll

1131
01:00:00,703 --> 01:00:01,723
get to do it for more.

1132
01:00:02,623 --> 01:00:07,064
And I think as long as I'm within that ethical territory,

1133
01:00:07,745 --> 01:00:10,365
I'm not that fussy about what it is,

1134
01:00:10,925 --> 01:00:14,266
because it's this weird, wonderful, absorbing task

1135
01:00:14,406 --> 01:00:15,747
that I'm nowhere near tired of yet.

1136
01:00:19,010 --> 01:00:23,999
I just want to say I really loved your talk and the really personal, wander-y style you

1137
01:00:24,019 --> 01:00:24,260
used.

1138
01:00:25,382 --> 01:00:29,589
I think it's fantastic and very honest and I appreciate that.

1139
01:00:30,691 --> 01:00:31,332
Now for my question.

1140
01:00:33,974 --> 01:00:36,856
You've talked a lot about, or hinted at your design process,

1141
01:00:37,056 --> 01:00:39,498
and it seems to be pretty rigorous and rational.

1142
01:00:40,259 --> 01:00:42,060
But also, I think a lot of people in free-to-play,

1143
01:00:42,100 --> 01:00:44,602
especially in mobile, feel that there's an element of luck

1144
01:00:45,262 --> 01:00:47,124
to a game becoming a smash hit.

1145
01:00:48,144 --> 01:00:50,686
And I would like your thoughts on that.

1146
01:00:50,726 --> 01:00:54,469
Do you believe, for example, Dots was mostly genius

1147
01:00:54,489 --> 01:00:55,190
with a bit of luck?

1148
01:00:55,330 --> 01:00:57,691
Do you feel like it was a lot of luck with a bit of genius,

1149
01:00:58,272 --> 01:01:00,654
or hard work, or good process, or, you know?

1150
01:01:01,534 --> 01:01:04,375
coming from a good design thing.

1151
01:01:05,416 --> 01:01:07,317
Yeah, that's my ill-formed question for you.

1152
01:01:08,657 --> 01:01:13,379
I mean, the cheat answer to that is

1153
01:01:13,679 --> 01:01:14,580
it's always about the work,

1154
01:01:14,780 --> 01:01:17,581
and the work needs to be perfect,

1155
01:01:17,721 --> 01:01:19,802
and then luck is the thing on top of that.

1156
01:01:19,862 --> 01:01:20,882
But I don't think you believe that,

1157
01:01:20,902 --> 01:01:22,443
and I know I don't believe that.

1158
01:01:23,043 --> 01:01:23,704
I mean, I'll tell you this.

1159
01:01:23,864 --> 01:01:25,444
The last game I launched was Dots & Co.,

1160
01:01:26,645 --> 01:01:29,086
and we launched it two weeks after a thing.

1161
01:01:29,106 --> 01:01:29,826
Was it?

1162
01:01:31,079 --> 01:01:33,400
Pokemon Go was that game?

1163
01:01:34,260 --> 01:01:37,661
Yeah, so that just changes the fundamental dynamics

1164
01:01:37,721 --> 01:01:40,282
of the App Store charts in a way

1165
01:01:40,302 --> 01:01:41,343
that you have no control over.

1166
01:01:43,443 --> 01:01:44,944
And that was very different from when

1167
01:01:44,984 --> 01:01:49,105
we launched our previous game, where the App Store wins

1168
01:01:49,145 --> 01:01:50,946
blue in our direction, not against us.

1169
01:01:51,826 --> 01:01:54,787
And so that kind of thing.

1170
01:01:57,027 --> 01:02:01,068
It's like a really identifiable quantifiable kind of luck.

1171
01:02:01,128 --> 01:02:03,209
Like that's not some weird, you know,

1172
01:02:03,489 --> 01:02:04,729
touchy feely, don't know.

1173
01:02:11,251 --> 01:02:13,272
Here's, I guess,

1174
01:02:14,092 --> 01:02:17,914
maybe my slightly more sophisticated cheat answer here,

1175
01:02:17,934 --> 01:02:22,975
is we are really bad at clearly differentiating

1176
01:02:23,015 --> 01:02:24,276
between luck and capital.

1177
01:02:26,697 --> 01:02:30,358
One of the reasons that nothing we did at Hide and Seek

1178
01:02:30,398 --> 01:02:31,998
ever got off the ground was it was partly because

1179
01:02:32,199 --> 01:02:33,499
we had too many things going on,

1180
01:02:33,659 --> 01:02:34,839
and in some cases I'm sure it was probably

1181
01:02:34,859 --> 01:02:35,800
because we were bad at our jobs.

1182
01:02:36,460 --> 01:02:38,961
But we could never afford more than one roll of the dice.

1183
01:02:39,101 --> 01:02:40,561
We'd put this thing out there and if it didn't work,

1184
01:02:41,662 --> 01:02:42,802
we weren't gonna eat that month,

1185
01:02:42,822 --> 01:02:44,403
so we had to run and do something else instead.

1186
01:02:45,443 --> 01:02:46,203
Big companies.

1187
01:02:47,428 --> 01:02:49,970
get lucky, because they can try over and over.

1188
01:02:49,990 --> 01:02:53,432
And that doesn't even necessarily look like

1189
01:02:55,813 --> 01:02:56,714
launching a thing that doesn't work

1190
01:02:56,734 --> 01:02:57,494
and then launching a new thing

1191
01:02:57,514 --> 01:02:58,495
and then launching a new thing.

1192
01:02:59,836 --> 01:03:01,517
2Dots has been alive for three years.

1193
01:03:01,937 --> 01:03:03,438
Over the course of that three years,

1194
01:03:03,859 --> 01:03:05,740
we've been able to make all kinds of additions

1195
01:03:05,800 --> 01:03:07,761
and amends and alterations to it.

1196
01:03:08,341 --> 01:03:10,263
We've been able to bring it out on extra platforms,

1197
01:03:10,283 --> 01:03:11,644
we've been able to do all of these things.

1198
01:03:12,884 --> 01:03:14,886
You know, that's a game that's been commercially successful

1199
01:03:14,906 --> 01:03:15,586
all the way through,

1200
01:03:16,647 --> 01:03:16,887
but...

1201
01:03:18,522 --> 01:03:20,604
if we hadn't been a studio with income,

1202
01:03:20,624 --> 01:03:22,165
if we hadn't been a studio with investment,

1203
01:03:23,006 --> 01:03:24,467
had we hit more bumps in the road,

1204
01:03:24,547 --> 01:03:25,488
they would have killed us dead

1205
01:03:25,528 --> 01:03:26,889
and we wouldn't have been able to do anything about it.

1206
01:03:30,055 --> 01:03:34,960
I'm not saying luck still isn't a factor, but when you look at a specific thing and

1207
01:03:35,000 --> 01:03:39,585
think well those specific people got lucky, it's worth broadening your examination of

1208
01:03:39,625 --> 01:03:43,789
the odds to say well how many rolls of the dice did they get, and how many rolls of the

1209
01:03:43,809 --> 01:03:48,574
dice am I going to get, and how do I sustain myself through those things.

1210
01:03:48,934 --> 01:03:51,116
And then you just try and get smart about the other stuff.

1211
01:03:52,077 --> 01:03:52,478
